%% Pattern Documentation
%% ==================
%% Pattern Name: Parallel Orchestration
%% Article: Article 2 - Multi-Agent Coordination Patterns
%%
%% Pattern Description:
%% Parallel Orchestration distributes independent tasks across multiple agents that work
%% simultaneously. A distributor fan-out sends work to workers, and an aggregator fan-in
%% collects and synthesizes results. Speed through massive parallelization.
%%
%% Business Value:
%% - Speed: 10-100x faster than sequential for independent tasks
%% - Cost: Better resource utilization (parallelism reduces idle time)
%% - Scalability: Add workers without changing architecture
%% - Comprehensive: Analyze from multiple angles simultaneously
%%
%% Key Characteristics:
%% 1. Independent Execution: Tasks don't depend on each other
%% 2. Concurrent Workers: Multiple agents process simultaneously
%% 3. Result Aggregation: Combine results from all workers
%% 4. Fan-Out/Fan-In: Distribute work, collect results
%% 5. Timeout Handling: Proceed with partial results if needed
%%
%% Real-World Use Cases:
%% 1. Real-Time Market Analysis
%%    - 15 agents analyzing different indicators in parallel
%%    - Result: 45 seconds â†’ 3 seconds, +180bp alpha, -60% cost
%%
%% 2. Quality Assurance Testing
%%    - Test UI, API, database, performance in parallel
%%    - Result: 8 hours â†’ 1 hour test suite execution
%%
%% 3. Data Pipeline Processing
%%    - Transform multiple data sources simultaneously
%%    - Result: Process 1M records in minutes, not hours
%%
%% 4. Multi-Modal Content Analysis
%%    - Analyze image, text, audio, video in parallel
%%    - Result: Complete analysis in seconds
%%
%% 5. Customer Service Triage
%%    - Check inventory, pricing, warranty, status in parallel
%%    - Result: 60 second response time to complex queries
%%
%% 6. Risk Assessment
%%    - Evaluate credit, fraud, compliance, operational risk in parallel
%%    - Result: Holistic risk profile in seconds
%%
%% Implementation Patterns:
%% - Dynamic Worker Pooling: Scale workers based on load
%% - Partial Result Handling: Proceed with minimum required responses
%% - Result Merging: Combine partial results intelligently
%% - Timeout Strategy: Hard timeout or grace period
%% - Error Isolation: One worker failure doesn't stop others
%%
%% When To Use:
%% âœ“ Tasks that are independent and parallelizable
%% âœ“ Need comprehensive multi-perspective analysis
%% âœ“ Speed is critical competitive advantage
%% âœ“ Have sufficient computational resources
%% âœ“ Can tolerate partial failures with graceful degradation
%%
%% When NOT To Use:
%% âœ— Tasks with strong dependencies (use sequential)
%% âœ— Resource-constrained environments
%% âœ— Where consistency across all results is mandatory
%%
%% Performance Characteristics:
%% - Latency: Maximum of all worker latencies (not additive)
%% - Throughput: Scales with number of workers
%% - Scalability: Horizontal (add more workers)
%% - Resilience: Medium (partial failures manageable)
%% - Cost: Lower per-task when parallelizable
%%
%% Aggregation Strategies:
%% 1. Voting: Majority rule for decisions
%% 2. Consensus: Agreement-based synthesis
%% 3. Ranking: Select top N results
%% 4. Merging: Combine all results into single output
%% 5. Learning: LLM synthesizes diverse inputs
%%
%% Related Patterns:
%% - Sequential Orchestration: For dependent tasks
%% - Supervisor Pattern: For dynamic task distribution
%% - Competitive Pattern: Multiple approaches to same problem
%% - Network/Swarm: Decentralized parallel execution
